Let's assume a reasonable size, say 1000 characters. So declare a char array of size 1000.

- Trimming the newline: after fgets, check if the last character is '\n' and replace it with '\0'.

- The loops: first loop to count, then loop to modify the string. Wait, modifying the string in place. Because in C, strings are arrays, so we can modify them in place. So code outline:

#include <stdio.h>
#include <ctype.h>

int main() {
    char txt[1000];
    int cu = 0, cl = 0;
    fgets(txt, sizeof(txt), stdin);
    // Remove newline
    size_t len = strlen(txt);
    if (len > 0 && txt[len - 1] == '\n') {
        txt[len - 1] = '\0';
    }
    // Count
    for (int i = 0; txt[i] ! = '\0'; i++) {
        if (islower(txt[i])) {
            cl++;
        } else {
            cu++;
        }
    }
    // Convert
    for (int i = 0; txt[i] ! = '\0'; i++) {
        if (cu > cl) {
            txt[i] = toupper(txt[i]);
        } else {
            txt[i] = tolower(txt[i]);
        }
    }
    printf("%s\n", txt);
    return 0;
} Wait, but in the original Python code, even if cu and cl are equal, it uses lower case. Because the condition is 'if cu > cl: upper else lower'. So in the C code, same logic. Testing this code with sample inputs. Sample input: "Hello"

Original Python code: counts H (uppercase), e, l, l, o (lowercase). So cu=1, cl=4. So output is lower: "hello". In C code, same counts. Then converted to lowercase.

